The tool inserts the semicolon markers that break the procedural T-SQL files into parseable queries the lineage tool can consume, without altering the original logic. It does this by reading sqlglot's token stream (the raw sequence of keywords and symbols) rather than relying on the parser, which is what lets it handle files the parser cannot, placing a semicolon before every token that starts a new statement, including statements nested inside BEGIN/END, TRY/CATCH, IF/WHILE, and procedure bodies. Every inserted delimiter carries a visible marker, ; /* [AUTOMATED DELIMITER] */, so each change is searchable, countable, auditable, and reversible, with no silent edits. It recognises these statement boundaries by structural pattern, built up iteratively from a preset of common statement constructs and then extended to special cases such as EXEC and OFFSET...FETCH paging, supported by common-sense validation rules like the operator-position check that stops a delimiter from landing mid-expression. It applies confident edits and withholds uncertain ones, routing those files to review with a precise explanation. The decision logic is regression-tested and version-controlled, and a sample of output is validated against the live parser before use. Every exception identified through manual checks has been resolved in the decision logic, with the approach biased toward preventing over-delimitation.
